#format #spec

> The .eshp file format specification.

The .eshp file format.

  #tag1 #tag2

  \> Short one-line description shown whenever this note is referenced.

  Free text body — prose, decisions, context, warnings.

  \.relationship-name
  -> target-slug
  <- source-slug

  \.another-rel
  -> other-slug

Rules:
- First non-empty line(s) that consist only of #tokens → tag line(s)
- Blank line after tags ends the tag section; body begins
- A line starting with > is the description (stripped, stored as desc field)
- A line starting with . (but not ..) opens a named relationship block
- -> lines inside a rel block = outgoing edges
- <- lines inside a rel block = incoming edges (stored reversed in DB)
  TRAP: <- takes ONLY the slug, never the rel name.
    ✓  <- other-slug
    ✗  <- related other-slug   ← this stores "related other-slug" as the src slug (ghost node!)
- A blank line ends a relationship block; content after goes back to body
- Slugs are root-relative POSIX paths without .eshp extension; top-level notes use plain stem
  e.g. eshp/store.eshp → store   |   eshp/concepts/auth.eshp → concepts/auth
- Relationship targets must use the full path-slug (e.g. -> concepts/auth, not -> auth)
- Tags: # prefix only in file, stripped everywhere else (DB, EshpNote.tags)
- Desc: > prefix only in file, stripped everywhere else (DB, EshpNote.desc)
- Escape: \ at start of a (stripped) line removes its special meaning
    \.foo  → body text starting with .  (not a relationship header)
    \>     → body text starting with >  (not a description)
    \\     → body text starting with \
- render_eshp() is the canonical serialiser — use it, don't hand-roll

.related
-> parser
-> edge-direction
